    <name>
				<text>37.3.3.1 The Poisson Process: Large metal sheets</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Large sheets of metal have faults in random positions but on average have \(1\) fault per \(10\) m<span class="math inline">\(^2\)</span>.</p>
<p>What is the probability that a sheet {@sheet@}&nbsp;m\(^2\) will have at most one fault?</p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<p>Poisson Process. In a sheet size {@sheet@} \(m^2\) <strong>we expect</strong> {@faults@} faults, therefore \(\lambda = \text{E}(X) = {@faults@}\).</p>
<p>Recall that the Poisson mass function is \(\text{P}(X=r) = \lambda^r e^{-\lambda}/r!\) for \(r = 0,1,2,\ldots\).</p>
<p>So, \(\text{P}(X\le 1) = \text{P}(X=0) + \text{P}(X=1) = {@decimalplaces(prob0, 4)@} + {@decimalplaces(prob1, 4)@} = {@tans1@}\) to 4 decimal places.</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
